%S A389507 4,16,16,28,28,40,56,64,76
%N A389507 Largest even number that is not the sum of two elements coprime to the primorial prime(n)# and each bounded by prime(n)#.
%C A389507 More values are added in a-file, which are heuristically correct (bounded by 5000 during the computation) assuming the following stronger form of Goldbach's conjecture: Every even integer larger than some 2*q+o(q) can be written as the sum of two primes larger than q.
%C A389507 The latter is intuitively true, since 2*q+2*x has x possible pairs, which are both prime with a chance of 1/log^2(2*q+2*x), and (1-1/log^2(2*q+2*x))^x ~ exp(-x/log^2(2*q+2*q)) is very small once x>>q^eps.
%C A389507 Equivalently, one can define a:=a(n) as the largest even integer such that for every integer 1 <= k <= a/2, (a-k)*k always has a prime factor bounded by prime(n) in its prime factorization.
%C A389507 Based on, but not identical to Erdős Problem 854 (see Bloom link).
%H A389507 Thomas Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/854">Problem 854</a>, Erdős Problems.
%H A389507 Stijn Cambie, <a href="/A389507/a389507.txt">Heuristically determined values</a>
%F A389507 a(n) = A002110(n) - A389506(n).
%e A389507 For n=2, a(2)=4 since prime(2)# = 6, the numbers coprime to 6 bounded by 6 are 1 and 5, 6=1+5, but 4 cannot be written as the sum of two elements in {1,5}.
%o A389507 (SageMath)
%o A389507 def a(n):
%o A389507     N=prod(Primes()[0:n]); b=1000;
%o A389507     R=[a for a in range(1, min(N, b)) if gcd(N, a)==1];
%o A389507     S=[j+i for (i, j) in Combinations(R, 2)]
%o A389507     for i in R: S.append(2*i);
%o A389507     S=set(S)
%o A389507     for i in range(min(N, b), 0, -2):
%o A389507         if i not in S: return i
%o A389507 (PARI) a(n) = my(lim = vecprod(primes(n)), s=setbinop((x,y)->x+y, select(x->(gcd(x, lim)==1), [1..lim]))); s=select(x->x<=lim, s); forstep(m=vecmax(s), 2, -2, if(!vecsearch(s, m), return(m))); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Oct 17 2025
